#* {{quote-book|en|author=F[rank] R[obert] Palmer|authorlink=Frank R. Palmer|chapter=Subjunctive and Irrealis|title=Mood and Modality|series=Cambridge Textbooks in Linguistics|edition=2nd|location=Cambridge, Cambridgeshire|publisher={{w|Cambridge University Press}}|year=2001|page=191|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=xKUvDFTARR8C&pg=PA191|isbn=978-0-521-80035-8|passage=Indeed, [[w:Thomas Givon|[Thomas] Givón]] (1994: 323) suggests the '''habitual''' is a 'hybrid modality', sharing some features of realis (higher assertive certainty) and some of irrealis ('lack of specific temporal reference; lack of specific evidence;&nbsp;…').}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Elly van Gelderen|chapter=Aspect: The Tense Aspect Parameter and Inner to Outer Aspect|title=Grammaticalization as Economy|series=Linguistik Aktuell = Linguistics Today|seriesvolume=71|location=Amsterdam; Philadelphia, Pa.|publisher={{w|John Benjamins Publishing Company}}|year=2004|section=section 5 (Giorgi & Pianesi: The Demise of the Infinitival Ending and Aspect)|page=221|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=e7yG6WSuwi8C&pg=PA221|isbn=978-90-272-2795-9|issn=0166-0829|passage=Stative verbs such as ''know'' and ''see'' are not associated with [+perf] since, like '''habituals''', they are associated with a generic operator.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Raymond Hickey|authorlink=Raymond Hickey|chapter=The Emergence of Irish English|title=Irish English: History and Present-day Forms|series=Studies in English Language|location=Cambridge, Cambridgeshire|publisher={{w|Cambridge University Press}}|year=2007|page=216|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=p3vDuPNG7nUC&pg=PA216|isbn=978-0-521-85299-9|passage=As an expression of the iterative '''habitual''' suffixal ''-s'' is by no means recent. It is found in emigrant letters from the early nineteenth century. [...] O'Hara's uses as an inflected first person singular as an iterative '''habitual''', e.g. ''I hopes the'' [&nbsp;] ''family are well&nbsp;…, I hopes you will except [sic!] my thanks for the same&nbsp;…'' (Kean O'Hara, 1818–19). This usage is still to be found in east coast varieties of Irish English.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Howard Jackson|chapter=Grammar: Morphology and Syntax|title=Key Terms in Linguistics|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum]]|year=2007|page=23|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=3XPUAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA23|isbn=978-0-8264-8741-4|passage=For example, repeated occurrence (''iteratives'' or ‘'''habituals'''’) in English may be signalled by {{underline|repeatedly}} or {{underline|several times}} (‘He shouted {{underline|repeatedly}}’), or it may be part of the meaning of the verb (‘The bird {{underline|fluttered}} its wings’).}}

